<h3>Participating in a Survey</h3>

<a name="matching"></a>
<h4>Matching your job with the survey job title and description</h4>

<p>The first step to participating in a survey is to match one or more of your firm's jobs to the survey job. The job
titles will rarely be an exact match, so you will need to use the survey job's description and qualifications. Use these
details to find the jobs at your firm that best match the survey job. If you are unsure, you can ask the survey sponsor
for clarification.</p>

<a name="asking"></a>
<h4>Asking a question of the survey sponsor</h4>

<p>The anonymous discussion board allows you to ask questions of the survey sponsor. For example, you might need
clarification the survey job's description or qualifications. Beneath the survey job description you will find a heading
titled "Questions &amp; Clarifications". Click "Ask something now" to fill in a question. The survey sponsor will be
notified of your question, and you will be notified as soon as the question has been addressed. All organizations
participating in a survey can view these questions, and they are anonymous.</p>

<p>When filling out a question, be sure to be as clear and concise as possible. It is also very important that you do
not give away any personally identifiable information in your post. Your anonymity is critical to protecting the
integrity of your data.</p>

<a name="responding"></a>
<h4>Responding to a survey</h4>

<p>Click the "Respond Now" button on the survey information page. This will bring you to the response form which will
consist of a variety of different questions. Be sure to read the questions carefully before responding. You can change
your responses up until the participation deadline, but you cannot make further changes once the survey report has been
distributed.</p>

<p>The different types of questions a survey may ask have different requirements. Numeric and percent fields require
numeric data and do not allow text. Multiple choice questions require you to select only one of the provided answers.
Pay and wage response fields require currency values, and in many cases you must also select either annual or hourly
terms.</p>

<p>Some surveys include required questions. The survey sponsor decided that these questions are very important and that
you cannot participate in the survey unless you provide data for these questions.</p>

<p>Some survey questions will have follow-up questions that are indented and disabled initially. These questions are
related to the question above and they become enabled once you have responded to the parent question.</p>

<p>Many questions will have an "Add Comment" link. Use this comment field to clarify your response if you feel more
explanation is needed. These comments will show up on the final report and will be visible to everybody. Be sure that
you do not give away any personally identifiable information.</p>

<a name="viewing"></a>
<h3>Viewing survey reports</h3>

<p>Survey reports are made available once the participation deadline for the survey has passed and the survey has at
least five participants. If there were not enough participants, results will not be made available until the sponsor
invites more organizations. When only some questions have enough data to report, the sponsor may choose to either extend
the participation deadline or generate the report as is. Once the report is generated, all participants will receive an
email notifying them that results are available.</p>

<p>If you are logged in, the side bar on the left contains links to your recent reports. Clicking on the job title of
the survey you wish to view will take you directly to that report. On the bottom of the side bar is a link to all
results.</p>

<a name="choosing"></a>
<h4>Choosing an annual or hourly wage format</h4>

<p>Our reports default to showing wage data in annualized format. You can change this to hourly format by clicking on
the "Show wages in Hourly Format" link at the top of the report. Click the link again to change the data back to hourly
format. The wage format displayed on the page also affects the downloaded reports. For example, if you wish to download
a PDF copy of the report in hourly format, first change the displayed report from annual to hourly format.</p>

<a name="downloading"></a>
<h4>Downloading reports</h4>

<p>CompSage reports can be downloaded as PDF, Word, or Excel format. This makes it easy for you to format the report in
a way that is relevant for you and your organization. You will find the download links on the upper right of the report
page.</p>

<a name="reporting"></a>
<h4>Reporting incorrect survey data</h4>

<p>Sometimes you may suspect that a report contains data that is incorrect. A participant may have made a typo, matched
the wrong job, or entered data into the wrong fields. You can report incorrect data by clicking the "Suspect incorrect
data?" link at the bottom of the report page. You will be asked to fill out a short description of why you think the
data is incorrect. We will then review the raw data and determine if a data entry error has been made and, if necessary,
correct the data. All online reports will be updated to reflect any changes made, although downloaded reports will not
be updated.</p>

